            },
            "answer_text": "I translate (on a professional basis with varying permutations of proficiency and specialisation) from six Western European languages (NL, FR, IT, DE, PT, ES) into English, and I can say with reasonable confidence that German source texts always require substantially more sentence-rearranging than any of the others. The apparent similarity of the simplest declarative sentences in EN and DE hides a great deal of conceptual rebuilding work later on. (For the record, Dutch has the verb-final stuff but mostly far closer-to-English clause structures apart from intermittent adjectival clause embedding; Italian sentences mostly just need splitting up and the occasional inversion, French largely involves looking at sentences and thinking \u201cwe just wouldn\u2019t say that at all\u201d). ",
