                "href": "/profile/Joe-Roberts-41"
            },
            "answer_text": "I\u2019ll take a different approach form the other respondents, and say that it depends on your definition of the word grammar. English and German punctuation marks and conventions are identical. (If there are any exceptions, please point them out to me, and I\u2019ll edit my answer.) A question mark, full stop/period, comma, exclamation point: these have the same meanings in both languages. The other respondents are quite right that broader \u201cgrammatical\u201d issues such as word order and even appropriate placement of punctuation are different in the two languages, but the meaning of \u201cgrammar\u201d in a limited sense is the same. Of course the words and meanings of words are different in the two languages, so if you start from that premise, you can\u2019t get much beyond punctuation (which is a form of grammar) and expect similarity. ",
